SmBaMn$_{2}$O$_{6}$ undergoes several structural and magnetic phase transitions with changing temperature (Sagayama, 2014; Chen, 2019): \begin{itemize} \item Below 190K the structure is in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2C6D_oP40_26_2a_2c_2a2b4c_2b-001}{a polar orthorhombic phase with space group $Pmc2_{1}$ \#26}. \item Between 190K and 362 K the structure is in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2C6D_oP80_62_2c_2d_2c5d_d-001}{a non-polar orthorhombic phase with space group $Pnma$ \#62}. \item Above 362 K the structure is in \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2C6D_oC40_65_g_n_ijklm_h-001}{quadrupled perovskite orthorhombic phase with space group $Cmmm$ \#65} (this structure). \item In the high temperature phase the samarium and barium sites may be disordered, in which case the system is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_cP5_221_a_c_b-001}{cubic perovskite ($E2_{1}$) structure}. ~ \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 Here we use the structural information from (Sagayama, 2019) at 400K. 
 The cubic perovskite phase may be recovered from this structure by replacing the barium atoms by samarium, setting $a = b = c$, and setting all variable Wyckoff position parameters to 1/4.
